Amby Bole	One of the infamous Bole brothers, a retired Mott Irregular, and a newfound shareholder of the Trygalle Trade Guild. Barely out of his teens, he shares with his brother Jula a rivalry over Precious Thimble and a family reputation for ferocity against mages and magic. Illiterate but stubbornly earnest, he avoids important people on the practical grounds that they tend to draw fire. Like his brother, he is rough, resilient, and guided by a mixture of swamp-born cunning, rivalry, and blunt survival instinct.<br>
Aranatha	A Tiste Andii formerly of Drift Avalii, related to Anomander Rake and raised among Nimander, Phaed, Skintick, Kedeviss, Nenanda, and Desra under Andarist's protection. She has long black hair, black skin, and startled silver eyes. Tremulous, diffident, and child-like, she is marked by an optimism others regard as disconnected from reality. Despite that air of fragility, she is coldly competent with a sword.<br>
Bainisk	A sixteen-year-old overseer in Chuffs, a camp at the Eldra Iron Mongers mine outside Darujhistan. Born in the mine and never having left it, he is among the older children there and leads the moles, the smaller children sent crawling into tight and dangerous spaces. Mine life has marked him heavily: half his face is shiny scar tissue around bright blue eyes, and his few cherished possessions include a small ivory-handled knife, a handful of coppers, and an old silver coin showing Darujhistan's skyline.<br>
Bedek	A Darujhistan man married to Myrla and known to Harllo as an uncle. A former caravan rider and colleague of Stonny Menackis and Gruntle, he lives with his indigent family in the Trench, a slum in the Gadrobi District. An accident left him without both legs below the knees, and his household depends on fragile, improvised support. His life is marked by poverty, injury, and the strain of caring for children in harsh circumstances.<br>
Bellam Nom	A fifteen-year-old of House Nom, distant relative of Rallick and Torvald Nom, and a student of Murillio at the duelling school founded by Stonny Menackis. Awkward from a recent growth spurt that leaves him all elbows and knees, he resembles Rallick and has sharp ears and a natural talent for lip reading. People find it difficult to keep secrets around him, giving the young student an unusual perceptiveness beneath his adolescent awkwardness.<br>
Chillbais	A small male demon who serves Baruk. Among his own kin he is a giant: heavy as a badger, squat and obese, with sculpted muscles beneath a prickly hide, stony eyes, needle fangs, stubby hands, and leathery wings that seem nearly too small to lift him. Bald, knobbled, watchful, and capable of an impossibly broad grin, he can sit motionless for months. He has a sharp tongue and a poor relationship with Crone.<br>
Desra	A Tiste Andii formerly of Drift Avalii, related to Anomander Rake and raised among Nimander, Phaed, Skintick, Aranatha, Nenanda, and Kedeviss under Andarist's protection. Attractive, ambitious, and ruthless, she sees power as the means to freedom and divides the world sharply between strong and weak. Clear-eyed about self-preservation, she can be hard, calculating, and contemptuous, though she recognises quiet strength when she sees it.<br>
Ditch	A former wizard of Pale associated with Dragnipur. Big and rough-looking, with angular, brutish features, he appears more like a career thug or alley-pouncer than a practitioner of sorcery. The contrast between his physical impression and magical background makes him a stark, uneasy figure among those connected to the sword's dark interior world.<br>
Endest Silann|Silann	An elderly Tiste Andii High Mage who serves Anomander Rake and is counted among the oldest of his people. Once a formidable sorcerer, he regards himself with weary modesty in Black Coral, more castellan than great mage. Slim, black-skinned, with almond-shaped eyes and brush-cut black hair shot with grey, he carries a deeply tired view of mortals and faith shaped by great age, memory, and long service.<br>
Faint	A shareholder in the Trygalle Trade Guild and part of Master Quell's caravan. She rides atop the carriage beside Glanno Tarp and wears practical protection when travelling through the Warrens, including a scaled hauberk and iron skullcap. Round-faced and linked to Sweetest Sufferance, she belongs to the Guild's dangerous, eccentric world of shareholders, drivers, mages, and impossible journeys.<br>
Gaz	A former fisherman from Darujhistan who lost his fingers in Lake Azur, leaving only thumbs and rows of knuckles. Embittered by injury, he turns to drink and violence and lives with his wife Thordy in a ramshackle house in a poor stretch of the Gadrobi District. Laconic and grim, he values brevity in words and thought, while his household depends on Thordy's small market trade in vegetables.<br>
Glanno Tarp	A shareholder in the Trygalle Trade Guild and carriage driver for Master Quell. Prone to malapropisms and offbeat wagers, he often makes bets with Reccanto Ilk whose terms are vague enough to annoy his companion. Though Reccanto is known for poor eyesight, the driver may see even less clearly, perceiving anything beyond thirty paces as little more than vague blocks of shape. Romantic, eccentric, and reckless, he is sure either Sweetest Sufferance or Faint will one day be his wife.<br>
Gorlas Vidikas|Gorlas	First son of Darujhistan's noble House Tholius and an accomplished duellist. As a young man he is among the rivals for Challice D'Arle's attention, and his skill carries a perceptible cruel streak. His duelling style is aggressive and unyielding: he does not retreat even for advantage, instead pressing forward with lightning-fast attacks and surrendering nothing.<br>
Gradithan	A former Urdo in the army of the Pannion Domin and a member of the Liberators, an insurgent group opposed to the Tiste Andii presence in Black Coral. He moves with a band of former soldiers and the mage Monkrat, looking for weakness and opportunity around the pilgrim camp of the Redeemer. He refuses to be addressed by his old military rank, insisting that such titles no longer belong to anyone.<br>
Hanut Orr	A member of Darujhistan's Noble Council and nephew of Turban Orr. Closely associated with Shardan Lim and Gorlas Vidikas, he sees himself as part of the Council's new breed and has the arrogance of a dangerous duellist. Smooth-shaven, long-fingered, charming, and domineering, he is regarded by older councillors as a preening, fatuous example of House Orr's worst qualities.<br>
Humble Measure	A twenty-seven-year-old master ironmonger and owner of Eldra Iron Mongers in Darujhistan. The son of a One Eye Cat merchant and a Rhivi woman, he appears innocuous but is driven by ruthless ambition. His business roots him in the Gadrobi District, where iron, mines, hidden wealth, and civic influence intersect beneath a plain exterior.<br>
Jula Bole	One of the infamous Bole brothers, a retired Mott Irregular, and a newfound shareholder of the Trygalle Trade Guild. Barely out of his teens, he shares with Amby a rivalry over Precious Thimble and the Bole reputation for being ferocious against mages and magic. Illiterate and rough-edged, he resembles his brother closely in expression, voice, and stride, making the two a matched pair of swamp-born resilience and comic rivalry.<br>
Kadaspala	A blind Tiste Andii artist among the prisoners of Dragnipur. His eye sockets bear severe burn scars, his legs are missing below the hips, and he moves by dragging himself. He uses a sharpened bone as a stylus, painting with bloodwood and blackwood pitch. Disturbing, damaged, and intensely creative, he gives the sword's interior world a haunted artistic presence.<br>
Kedeviss	A Tiste Andii formerly of Drift Avalii, related to Anomander Rake and raised among Nimander, Phaed, Skintick, Aranatha, Nenanda, and Desra under Andarist's protection. She sees with intimidating clarity, her unyielding gaze leaving others torn between fear and love. Admired by Aranatha for cleverness and perception, she is one of the sharper minds in her small Andii group.<br>
Lazan Door	A tall, very thin man who travels with Madrun Badrun. Almost skeletal beside his broader companion, he is bald, with an ornate tattooed scene framed in gold thread stitched through the skin of his forehead. His teeth are capped in silver-tipped gold like fangs, and he wears a threadbare linen cloak long enough to drag behind him. He fights with a curved sword in each hand.<br>
Leff	A Darujhistan inhabitant and old criminal associate of Torvald Nom. Partnered with Scorch, he has worked as caravan guard, enforcer, Guild thug, and bounty hunter, and both men are known for a nasty streak. More grounded than his fidgety companion, he still moves in the same rough, practical world of paid violence, dubious employment, and streetwise improvisation.<br>
Lock	A new Hound of Shadow, huge but leaner and longer-necked than the older Shadow Hounds. Bone-white and even paler than Pallid, with onyx eyes, short white hair, and scars revealing dark blue skin beneath, he has a stark, spectral appearance. Though massive, he is still only half the weight of the fellow Hound Cast.<br>
Madrun	An enormous, broad-shouldered, oddly short-legged man with shaggy hair and a surprisingly well-spoken manner. He arrives in Darujhistan with Lazan Door dressed in flamboyant colours: bright vest, sky-blue silk blouse, black kerchief, vermillion pantaloons, and snug moccasins. The name is not his original one but was given during a job in One Eye Cat. He fights with a curved sword in each hand.<br>
Master Quell|Quell	A navigator, sorcerer, and merchant with the Trygalle Trade Guild based out of Darujhistan. Unlike shareholders who cling to the outside of the carriage during dangerous journeys, he remains inside its relative safety. Knowledgeable about important figures and world events, he keeps his caravans stocked with healing elixirs, unguents, and salves, including some of High Denul quality. He also suffers badly from kidney stones, an indignity that often intrudes on Guild travel.<br>
Myrla	A Darujhistan woman married to Bedek and known to Harllo as his aunt. She lives with her indigent family in the Trench, a slum in the Gadrobi District, and has a lined face and arthritic hands. Frequently exhausted and unable to work regularly, she mends clothes when she can. Her household is poor, crowded, and fragile, held together by improvised labour and care.<br>
Nenanda	A Tiste Andii formerly of Drift Avalii, related to Anomander Rake and raised among Nimander, Phaed, Skintick, Aranatha, Kedeviss, and Desra under Andarist's protection. Gripped by a deep, often unreasoning rage, he prefers plain talk and distrusts clever language, believing liars and thieves profit from confusion. He and Desra were once lovers.<br>
Pallid	A new Hound of Shadow. Bone-white, with onyx eyes, short white hair, and scars revealing dark blue skin beneath, this Hound is leaner and longer-necked than the older Shadow Hounds. Its stark colouring and scarred body give it a cold, spectral presence among Shadow's monstrous servants.<br>
Precious Thimble	A tiny, beautiful swamp witch and retired Mott Irregular who becomes a shareholder of the Trygalle Trade Guild. Her appearance suggests the child she once was never truly aged, and as a witch her soul can wander freely in the realm of dreams. She has some healing skill and is accompanied by Amby and Jula Bole, rival brothers whose competing affection she understands and manages to her own advantage. She is illiterate.<br>
Prophet Seech|Seech	A title used by Munug, a Darujhistan artisan and painter who crafts small objects from bone, jade, ivory, serpentine, and similar materials. In the Toll the Hounds Dramatis Personae he is identified as High Priest of the Fallen One. As Munug, he is an old, threadbare, pain-worn man with a broad forehead, wiry white eyebrows, narrow features, a weak jaw, and crooked jutting teeth.<br>
Reccanto Ilk	A Trygalle Trade Guild shareholder and member of Master Quell's caravan. He has watery grey eyes and poor eyesight, yet considers himself a master duellist with a rapier and sometimes fights with a saw-toothed knife. He often accepts Glanno Tarp's offbeat wagers while complaining that the terms are too vague and require greater precision, making him a fussy but willing participant in the Guild's eccentric camaraderie.<br>
Salind	High Priestess of the Cult of the Redeemer in the pilgrim camp surrounding the Barrow of the Redeemer outside Black Coral. She chose her own name only recently and is unsure how she came to hold priestly authority, but she possesses a sensitivity to the Redeemer's emotions that she relays to fellow believers. Young, with short shining black hair, large deep-brown eyes, a pale face, and a deep husky voice, she dresses in rough russet wool and green linen.<br>
Scorch	A Darujhistan inhabitant and old criminal associate of Torvald Nom, partnered with Leff. The two have worked as caravan guards, enforcers, Guild thugs, and bounty hunters, and both are known for a nasty streak. He wears an expression of perpetual surprise, speaks in tones of bewildered disbelief, and fidgets so constantly that even his partner can find it distracting.<br>
Seba Krafar	An assassin and mage serving as Master of Darujhistan's Assassins' Guild. Large, bearish, and naturally brutal in bearing, he is the sort of man others instinctively avoid even without knowing his profession. He struggles to hold another person's gaze for long and compensates by being bluntly honest and avoiding evasion. He prefers nondescript clothing, moccasins, and remaining out of public view when possible.<br>
Shardan Lim	A pure-blooded Daru noble of House Lim and member of Darujhistan's Noble Council. Closely associated with Hanut Orr and Gorlas Vidikas, he considers himself part of the Council's new breed and is an arrogant duellist. Tall and thin, with a parched face, washed-out blue eyes, hooked nose, and lipless mouth, he proudly displays a scarred and overdeveloped left wrist from successful duels.<br>
Sister Spite	A sorceress and Soletaken Eleint also known as Spite. Daughter of Draconus and sister to Envy, she is a stunning, ethereal beauty with haughtiness and regal bearing near caricature. Tall, ash-skinned, black-haired, and black-eyed, with perfect brows, full lips, and manicured nails, she carries herself with the airs of a coddled princess. Her long life leaves her with a weary edge beneath the hauteur.<br>
Skintick	A Tiste Andii formerly of Drift Avalii, related to Anomander Rake and raised among Nimander, Phaed, Nenanda, Aranatha, Kedeviss, and Desra under Andarist's protection. He has a long jester's face and is quick to smile, jest, mock, or answer with sarcasm. Others see him as unserious, treating existence itself as a joke, and he is not inclined toward prayers, especially to Mother Dark.<br>
Snell	Young son of Bedek and Myrla in Darujhistan, with sisters Mew and Hinty and an adopted cousin, Harllo. Squat and round-shouldered, he lives with his indigent family in the Trench, a slum in the Gadrobi District. A nasty brute who bullies the younger children, he sees the world as a threat to be dealt with before it deals with him.<br>
Sordiko Qualm	High Priestess of the Temple of Shadow in Darujhistan. Ridiculously tall, with an exquisitely moulded face, amber eyes, long straight rust-red hair, and a deep melodic voice, she wears a hooded robe. When greeting visitors she bends within the robe to appear only chest-height, hiding her face in shadow and altering her voice into something thin and whispery.<br>
Spinnock Durav	A Tiste Andii warrior and loyal, trusted subject of Anomander Rake. Considered by the Tiste Andii of Black Coral to be the finest warrior among them, he nonetheless sees himself as unsuited to military command. Large for an Andii, wide-shouldered and bearish, he has long unbound hair with a faint reddish tinge, forest-green tilted eyes, broad features, prominent cheekbones, and a grin that rarely fades. He bears a Hust sword, the heirloom of House Durav, and is a master of the ancient game Kef Tanar.<br>
Studlock|Studious Lock	Castellan of Lady Varada's estate in Darujhistan. Hooded and masked, with red unhuman eyes, he is wrapped in cotton swaddles that give him a pitter-patter gait, tiny feet almost like cloven hooves, and gloved hands folded like a praying mantis. His voice suggests gravel under fingernails or a bullying seagull. Eager to offer medical expertise, he gives diagnoses and treatments of dubious reliability.<br>
Sweetest Sufferance	A shareholder in the Trygalle Trade Guild and part of Master Quell's caravan. Short and plump, with soft brown eyes, a round face, small hands, and a waddling walk, she bears a name that suggests either maternal resignation or sharp irony. Those who know her can recognise hunger by the way she rubs her face and the look that enters her eyes. She fights with a pair of hatchets.<br>
Thordy	A Darujhistan vegetable vendor who grows produce in the small garden behind her home. Married to Gaz, she lives in a poor stretch of the Gadrobi District and relies on her garden as the household's source of income. Unable to have children and worn down by age and hard work, she presents the grounded, weary face of poverty in the city.<br>
Tiserra	A gifted potter in her early thirties with a modest home and workshop in Darujhistan. Wife of Torvald Nom, she is also an Adept with magical talent and the ability to read the Deck of Dragons. Her personal wooden Deck is a Barukan version that includes several unique cards of her own addition, blending craft, domestic life, and quiet divinatory skill.<br>
Venaz	A young worker in Chuffs, the workcamp at the Eldra Iron Mongers mine outside Darujhistan. Sold to the mine by his stepfather years earlier, he was once Bainisk's friend and favoured mole, but grew too large for the cramped tasks of that work. Jealous and hard-edged, he becomes the local tough among the mining children, leading a pack of younger boys eager to test his position.<br>
